Preliminaries: The site Traffic data

The data comes from a cooking recipe website. The company that owns the website wants to sell subscriptions, and the idea is that if the website receives a lot of visits (thus traffic is “high”) due to a posted recipe, the likelihood of a sale subscription increases.

So the overall goal of this project is to predict which recipes will lead to high traffic.

Data processing

In this section we will be required to clean our database for effective analysis. This will specifically involve recoding the variables, presenting the proportion of missing values for each variable and moving on to their processing if possible.

1-Recoding of variables and checking the validity of the data.

a- Recoding of the high-traffic variable and its validity.

## Structure display 

str(Data$high_traffic)
##  Factor w/ 1 level "High": 1 1 NA 1 NA 1 NA NA 1 NA ...

We note that the variable high-traffic has the modality 1 for all the recipes presenting a traffic package and NA for all the others. From the context of our study, we notice that when a recipe is visited more often it is marked High and therefore nothing (NA) when it is not. Therefore, we will assign the numerical code 0 for all recipes presenting NA, this means that these recipes have low traffic.

Data$trafic_recod<-ifelse(is.na(Data$high_traffic), 0, 1)
str(Data$trafic_recod)
##  num [1:947] 1 1 0 1 0 1 0 0 1 0 ...

Analysis of our new variable “trafic_recod” reveals that it is a binary numeric variable, taking the value 1 for high traffic recipes and 0 for others. This binary structure is particularly suited to our analysis objectives, in particular for the application of the different models planned (Linear Probability Model, Logit Model and Random Forest Model). Indeed, these models require a binary dependent variable, which fully justifies the validity of our recoded variable “trafic_recod” which is our new response variable.

Remark: 1=High,0=Lower

b- Missing values.

Data %>%
  summarise(across(-high_traffic, ~ mean(is.na(.x)))) %>%
  dplyr::select(dplyr::where(~ .x > 0))
## # A tibble: 1 × 4
##   calories carbohydrate  sugar protein
##      <dbl>        <dbl>  <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1   0.0549       0.0549 0.0549  0.0549

The calories, carbohydrate, sugar and protein variables have the same number of missing values, i.e. 5.49% of missing values, and those for the same recipes. In this case we can delete observations with missing values in the database for the following reasons. First, we have a small number of observations with missing values (52 observations out of 947) or 5.49%. By deleting them we will still keep 895 observations which is more than enough to train the different models and will less affect the statistical power of our analyzes as well as our results. Second, the fact that the missing values are for the same observations suggests that these are probably recipes for which this nutritional information was not provided. Thus, their deletion is safer in this case. Third, imputations can introduce bias into our analyses.

# Delete observations with missing values.
Data <- Data[!is.na(Data$calories) & !is.na(Data$protein)& !is.na(Data$sugar)& !is.na(Data$carbohydrate), ] 

# Show number of observations after cleaning
print(nrow(Data))
## [1] 895

From this result, we realize that there is no more missing data in the database. Thus, the database is clean and can be analyzed.

3-Division of the database into test data and training data.

This section consists of dividing our database into test data and training data in order to evaluate the predictability performance of our model. For this, we will put 60% of the observations in the training base and the remaining 40% in the test data.

set.seed(2453)
tr <- sample(nrow(Data), round(nrow(Data) * 0.6)) ## 60/40 split train/test
my_train <- Data[tr, ]
my_test  <- Data[-tr, ]

4-

a-Estimation of Models LPM and logit

# LPM model

modf1 <- trafic_recod~ category + calories + protein + sugar+ carbohydrate + servings

lm.fit1 <- lm(modf1 , data=my_train)

# Logit model

modf2 <- trafic_recod~ category + calories + protein + sugar+ carbohydrate + servings

lm.fit2 <-  glm(modf2 , family="binomial",data=my_train)

stargazer(lm.fit1,lm.fit2,
          dep.var.caption="",dep.var.labels="",
          omit.table.layout = "n", star.cutoffs = NA,no.space=TRUE,
          keep.stat=c("rsq","n"),
          header=FALSE,
          column.labels=c("LPM ", "LOGIT"),
          title="Aspect of trafic", type="text"
          )

    method = "cv",         # Cross-validation

6- Prediction of revenue traffic aspect and determination of the confusion factor of each model.

To evaluate the performance of the different models based on the confusion matrices, we will use the following matrices.

Metric evaluation of accuracy

Métrique Formule Description
Accuracy (VP + VN) / (VP + VN + FP + FN) Total correct proportion of prediction.
Sensibility VP / (VP + FN) Positive correct proportion of prediction
Recall VP / (VP + FN) Proportion of real positive case correctly identifies
Taux d'erreur 2 × (Precision × Recall) / (Precision + Recall) Erreur=1-Accuracy.
Specificity VN / (VN + FP) Proportion of real negative case correctly identifie.

Legend :

  • VP = True positive
  • VN = True Negative
  • FP = False positive
  • FN = False Negative

LPM model

predict1<-predict(lm.fit1,newdata=my_test)
class_lpm <- ifelse(predict1 > 0.5, 1, 0)
# Confusion_matrix
matrix1<-table(factor(class_lpm),factor(my_test$trafic_recod),dnn=c("prediction","truth"))
prop.table(matrix1,margin =1)
##           truth
## prediction         0         1
##          0 0.7519380 0.2480620
##          1 0.2358079 0.7641921
# manually compute accuracy, specificity & sensitivity
cat("accuracy: ", (matrix1[1,1] + matrix1[2,2]) / sum(matrix1), "\n")
## accuracy:  0.7597765

The model has an accuracy of about 76%, which is correct. It is significantly better than a random prediction. The specificity is good (85%), which means that it identifies negative cases well. However, sensitivity is lower (64%), indicating that he misses more positive cases.

RF model

#  Prediction with the model

## accuracy:  0.7290503

The model has an accuracy of about 73%, which is okay, but could be improved. It is significantly better than a random prediction (very low p-value). The specificity is good (84%), which means that the model identifies the negative cases well. However, the sensitivity is lower (58%), indicating that the model misses a significant proportion of positive cases.

Based on the confusion matrices, we notice that the logit model and LPM have practically the same performance in predicting the aspect of the traffic of the recipes studied. Also the analysis of the ROC curve of these three models shows that the model RF is less efficient compared to the other two knowing that the ROC curve of the logit model is almost everywhere significantly above that of LPM. This result is also confirmed by the AUC analysis of these three models. Subsequently, for a more flexible and relevant interpretability we choose among other things the logit model as the most efficient.

Interpretation of Logit model.

At the 5% threshold, we interpret the effect of the different explanatory variables as follows:

Categorical variables

  1. Breakfast (1.95365) :
    • Being in the “Breakfast” category increases the chances of having high traffic by approximately 1.95, compared to the Beverages category.
  2. Chicken (2.366162):
    • Being in the Chicken category increases the chances of having high traffic by approximately 2.36, compared to the Beverages category.
  3. Breast (2.727279):
    • Being in the “Chicken Breast” category multiplies the chances of having high traffic by approximately 15.29, compared to the Beverages category.
  4. Dessert (3.735893):
    • Being in the Dessert category multiplies the chances of having high traffic by approximately 3.73, compared to the reference category Beverages.
  5. Lunch/Snacks (3.970579):
    • Being in the Lunch/Snacks category increases the chances of having high traffic by approximately 3.97, compared to the Beverages category.
  6. Meat (3.679784):
    • Being in the Meat category increases the chances of having high traffic by approximately 39.64, compared to the Beverage category.
  7. One Dish Meal (3.907939):
    • Being in the One Dish Meal category increases the chances of having high traffic by approximately 3.90, compared to the Beverages category.
  8. Pork (5.187866):
    • Being in the Pork category increases the chances of having high traffic by approximately 5.18, compared to the Beverages category.
  9. Potato (5.182113):
    • Being in the Potato category increases the chances of having high traffic by approximately 5.18, compared to the Beverages category.
  10. Vegetable (6.576955):
    • Being in the Vegetable category increases the chances of having high traffic by approximately 6.57, compared to the Beverages category.

Quantitative variables

The variables Calories, Protein and Sugar reduce the chance that the recipes are visited more on the site, but the latter are not significant.

Conclusion

In conclusion, only the Category variable, depending on its modalities, seems to be a good predictor of the aspect of revenue traffic on the company’s site.

Recommendations for Increasing Site Traffic.

Based on previous results, revenue category is the variable that could have the greatest impact on increasing revenue traffic. We therefore make the following recommendations for an optimal traffic increase strategy:

  1. Highlight vegetable-based recipes:
    • Vegetable-based recipes seem to be the most popular. Make sure they are easily accessible on the site.
  2. **Highlight *Pork and Potato** recipes:
    • These two types of recipes also attract a lot of visitors, so it is crucial to give them pride of place on the site.
  3. **Promote recipes from the* *Dessert** category:
    • Recipes in the Dessert category also attract a large number of customers. Make sure they are clearly visible and highlighted.

Summary of Recommendations.

  • Prioritize vegetarian recipes, particularly vegetable-based recipes, to attract more visitors.
  • **Promote *Pork and Potato** recipes, which have great traffic potential.
  • Highlight desserts, a category that generates strong interest from visitors.

By comparing the estimates of the models (LPM and LOGIT) depending on whether observations containing missing values are removed, we establish that the estimated coefficients are almost the same and also have the same signs. Also, the coefficients of modality 6 as a snack for the variable servings are not estimated in the case where the NA are not deleted although modality 1 is taken as reference. As a result, we confirm the results according to which the models estimated under the hypothesis of the removal of NA are more efficient and do not distort the results.
